may have contained Nvidia (\u003Cspan class=\"ticker-hover-wrapper\"\u003ENASDAQ:\u003Ca title=\"NVIDIA Corporation\" men\u003Cspan class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003E involved were arrested last week and have been charged for suspected fraud. \"The case relates to servers with chips embedded in them coming into Singapore, and then from Singapore, they went to Malaysia,\" K. Shanmugam, Singapore's law minister, said on Monday.\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003E\"The question is, whether Malaysia was a final destination, or from Malaysia it went to somewhere else, which we do not know for certain at this point. Singapore has asked U.S. and Malaysia authorities for more information on the servers under \u003Ca title=\"investigation\" href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.mha.gov.sg\u002Fmediaroom\u002Fspeeches\u002Ftranscript-of-media-conference-with-mr-k-shanmugam-minister-for-home-affairs-and-minister-for-law-regarding-the-case-involving-the-three-men-who-were-charged-on-27-february-2025-for-fraud-by-false-representation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"\u003Einvestigation\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003EConcerns continue to grow over the effectiveness of U.S. export controls blocking China's access to advanced technology. \u003Cdiv\u003E \u003Cp id=\"description\"\u003EThe HCOB Eurozone Manufacturing PMI, a measure of the overall health of eurozone factories compiled by S&P Global, rose to 47.6 in February.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp\u003EThis was up from 46.6 at the start of the year and its highest level in two years, signalling\u003Cspan class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003E the smallest deterioration in the health of the euro area manufacturing industry since early-2023. \u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003EEuro area manufacturing production came close to stabilising midway through the first quarter, declining at a mild pace that was the softest in nine months.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003ENew orders received by eurozone factories fell at the weakest rate in almost three years.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003E\"Job cuts sped up in February, but it's not uncommon for layoffs to continue even after a recession ends. So, this doesn't necessarily mean a recovery is far off,\" Dr. Cyrus de la Rubia, Chief Economist at Hamburg Commercial Bank said.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003E\"It's still too early to call it a recovery, but the PMI hints that the manufacturing sector might be finding its footing. New orders are falling at the slowest pace since May 2022, and production is edging closer to stabilising. So, after almost three years of recession, we could see a bit of growth in the coming months.\" \u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003E \u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp manufacturing downturn eases in February","isPaywalled":false,"lastModified":"2025-03-03T04:38:15-05:00","status":"Active","content":"\u003Cp\u003E \u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp\u003EFrance Manufacturing PMI posted below the 50.0 no-change level in February, thereby marking 25 months of deteriorating operating conditions for French factories. However, with a reading of 45.8, this was up from 45.0 in January and signalled the shallowest contraction for nine months.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003EKey findings include: French goods producers post softer falls in output and new orders;input cost inflation ticks up to six-month high but charges up only slightly; business growth expectations at their strongest since last June.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E \u003Cp class=\"paywall-full-content invisible\"\u003E\"The decline is slowing. The state of the French manufacturing industry is so weak that a slower contraction signalled by the HCOB PMI in February is a small consolation. Flash PMI figures had already suggested that service providers are faring even worse, with their contraction intensifying. France's current crisis is arguably due to political reasons. Repeated no confidence votes and deep ideological divisions in Paris have gripped the economy. The recently concluded \"Artificial Intelligence Action Summit\" in Paris vividly demonstrated that France remains an attractive destination for investment compared to its European neighbours. The country should not squander its solid position through political infighting.\" \u003Ca title=\"said\"
